WEBVTT

00:10.700 --> 00:17.440
The Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and fantasy, presented

00:17.440 --> 00:20.080
by the Permian Basin Science Fiction Association.

00:23.640 --> 00:24.880
This is David Cruz.

00:24.880 --> 00:27.180
Daryl Lane and David Carson.

00:31.780 --> 00:34.300
The following show will be an interview with Frederick Poe.

00:35.100 --> 00:37.240
Poe knows science fiction as few other people do.

00:37.740 --> 00:42.700
He's been an editor of science fiction books and magazines, an agent who's handled some of the biggest names in the field,

00:43.120 --> 00:45.940
and an author who's won numerous Hugo and Nebula awards.

00:46.620 --> 00:50.500
In fact, he's the only individual to be awarded a Hugo as an author and as an editor.

00:51.440 --> 00:54.180
He began publishing science fiction in the late 1930s.

00:54.180 --> 00:58.700
Perhaps his best known work is The Space Merchants, written in collaboration with Cyril Kornbluth.

00:59.160 --> 01:02.820
The novel illustrates one of Poe's trademarks, satire and social criticism.

01:03.700 --> 01:07.080
One of his more recent novels, Gateway, won both Hugo and Nebula awards.

01:07.760 --> 01:11.040
In 1978, Poe published his memoirs, The Way the Future Was,

01:11.560 --> 01:16.160
a fascinating description of his interface with science fiction through a long and uniquely vital career.

01:16.780 --> 01:19.320
We can be grateful that his career is still alive and progressing.

01:28.720 --> 01:29.880
The Space Merchants

01:29.880 --> 01:31.760
The Space Merchants

01:31.760 --> 01:35.580
The Space Merchants

01:43.500 --> 01:46.900
Mr. Poe, you've written of how you grew up with science fiction,

01:47.040 --> 01:50.780
reading the pulps, organizing clubs, editing fanzines and so forth.

01:50.780 --> 01:56.940
Could you recall what it was that attracted you to science fiction so completely at such an early age?

01:57.560 --> 02:03.580
Well, I think it was basically the adventure, the kind of science fiction that was being published around 1930,

02:03.960 --> 02:05.480
when I first got in touch with it.

02:06.040 --> 02:12.520
When I first discovered that it existed, it was mostly space opera and gimmick stories

02:12.520 --> 02:18.080
and stories about exciting, adventurous exploits all over the galaxy.

02:18.640 --> 02:20.760
And that was in the middle of the Great Depression,

02:20.760 --> 02:25.780
and science fiction looked an awful lot better to me than the real world that I could see.

02:28.420 --> 02:35.800
Okay, I believe your first story was published around 1937. Is that correct around that time?

02:36.160 --> 02:39.360
The first thing I had published was a poem. It was an amazing story.

02:40.220 --> 02:47.480
I wrote it in 1935, and it was accepted in 1936 and published in 1937 and paid for in 1938.

02:48.500 --> 02:50.660
So somewhere in there I became a professional writer.

02:51.600 --> 02:54.520
The first story, I think, was probably in 1938.

02:54.740 --> 03:00.480
It was a collaboration with another writer, and it appeared in a astounding magazine that's now called Analog.

03:02.860 --> 03:07.860
Could you explain just a little bit about what the Futurians were and your part in the organization?

03:08.660 --> 03:16.260
Well, science fiction has some special traits, and one of them is that its readers herd together as much as they can.

03:17.180 --> 03:21.520
They form fan clubs and associations and correspondents groups and so on.

03:22.200 --> 03:28.920
And in New York City, there were quite a few science fiction fans, and about 25 or 30,

03:29.860 --> 03:33.400
most of whom wanted to be writers, formed a club called the Futurians.

03:34.160 --> 03:40.680
There were people like Cyril Karnbluth, Isaac Asimov, Damon Knight, and myself, quite a few others.

03:41.500 --> 03:48.380
Don Walheim, who's now the head of Dahl Books as an editor, and no batches of others

03:48.380 --> 03:54.000
who really desperately wanted to write science fiction or edit science fiction or something like that.

03:54.200 --> 03:57.420
Quite a few of them acted out their childhood fantasies and did it.

03:58.760 --> 04:06.820
And I'm not quite sure why the Futurians produced more science fiction writers than most of the other clubs.

04:06.980 --> 04:11.220
It probably has something to do with size. New York had a bigger pool of talent to draw from.

04:11.820 --> 04:17.780
The Los Angeles group also produced quite a few, including Ray Bradbury and Larry Niven and several others.

04:19.680 --> 04:25.360
Did you help each other in your writing? Was it sort of a brotherhood kind of thing? Were you aided each other?

04:25.360 --> 04:31.700
It was partly help and partly one-upmanship, putting each other down.

04:33.120 --> 04:41.900
We did discuss each other's work a lot, and I guess in the process of criticizing it, there was a lot of help given.

04:42.500 --> 04:51.020
I think the biggest factor that made it easier for a lot of us to go on with writing was just the knowledge with other people who were doing it.

04:51.020 --> 05:02.220
And also the fact that we collaborated a lot. We remedied each other's deficiencies by writing, by collaborating on single stories.

05:03.120 --> 05:11.700
And although most of the stories were not very good, we did learn something by seeing how other people would tackle the same subjects we were writing about.

05:15.300 --> 05:23.660
You're uniquely qualified, I think, to comment on science fiction since you've seen it from so many perspectives as a fan, an author, an agent, an editor, and so forth.

05:24.780 --> 05:28.940
You started the editing part of it when you were 19 years old, I think. Is that right?

05:29.480 --> 05:39.960
I was lucky enough to fall into a job as a professional magazine editor when I was 19. I had asked an editor I knew because I'd been trying to sell him stories without success.

05:40.680 --> 05:45.220
If he needed an assistant, and he was kind enough not to laugh out loud.

05:45.940 --> 05:50.520
I didn't know at the time that not very many science fiction magazine editors could afford assistance.

05:50.820 --> 05:55.420
But he mentioned to me another publishing company that was expanding and suggested I get a touch with them.

05:56.080 --> 06:00.100
So I did. It was popular publications, one of the biggest pulp houses of the time.

06:00.720 --> 06:06.800
And they were expanding, and they gave me a job at $10 a week to edit two professional science fiction magazines.

06:08.000 --> 06:11.740
$10 wasn't so bad. They hired other editors for nothing at the same time.

06:12.560 --> 06:16.980
And most of the material you got then was the pulp kind of stuff?

06:17.620 --> 06:23.060
It was mostly pulp, but it included a lot of the writers who are the mainstays of the field now.

06:23.220 --> 06:26.860
I published a lot of Isaac Asimov stuff because we were close friends.

06:27.280 --> 06:34.460
A few of Robert A. Heinlein's stories that his primary market, John Campbell, for one reason or other, didn't want to print.

06:35.360 --> 06:40.520
And Henry Kutner and A. E. Van Vot and Cleve Cartmille and Del Sprague de Camp.

06:42.160 --> 06:47.760
Most of the people who were writing at that time wound up in my magazine, not always with their best stories.

06:48.680 --> 06:52.440
In fact, very often with their worst stories, because I wasn't paying very much.

06:52.600 --> 06:54.840
I had a budget of about half a cent a word.

06:56.440 --> 07:00.940
One of the other lines of work that you got into, I remember, was as an advertising copywriter,

07:01.940 --> 07:05.080
which brings up to my mind the novel The Space Merchants.

07:05.640 --> 07:08.920
Well, actually The Space Merchants was sort of responsible for it.

07:08.920 --> 07:15.900
When I was in the Army, in the Air Force, in World War II, I had some spare time on my hands in Italy.

07:16.220 --> 07:22.680
And I decided to write a novel. And the most interesting subject I could think of was the advertising industry.

07:22.680 --> 07:27.640
So I wrote a whole novel about advertising. Very bad novel.

07:28.720 --> 07:32.840
After the war was over, I took it out and looked at it and realized that it was pretty bad.

07:33.100 --> 07:36.100
And one of its great defects was that I didn't know anything about advertising.

07:37.120 --> 07:42.180
So I went to the New York Sunday Times and looked in the classified section,

07:42.440 --> 07:46.560
found a couple of people advertising jobs in advertising,

07:47.540 --> 07:52.120
and applied and got one of them and spent about three years as an advertising copywriter.

07:52.120 --> 08:00.880
During that time, I looked over at this old novel again and realized that it had many more faults and ignorance.

08:02.020 --> 08:08.340
And I burned it and I had only basic information about advertising and no novel to put it in.

08:08.500 --> 08:12.200
So I thought of writing a science fiction novel. And it turned out to be The Space Merchants.

08:13.180 --> 08:21.280
Cyril Cornblith was a close friend of mine. We'd collaborated before the war, before we both went into service.

08:21.280 --> 08:29.900
And after I had written about a third of it, because a magazine editor wanted it in a hurry,

08:30.420 --> 08:35.360
I asked Cyril if he wanted to help me with it and he and I collaborated on it.

08:37.980 --> 08:42.280
What was your normal method of collaboration? How did you work out your scenario for the future?

08:43.080 --> 08:46.560
We didn't work them out in very great detail ahead of time.

08:47.560 --> 08:54.420
Mostly what Cyril and I did was to, simply, we wrote seven novels and a number of short stories together.

08:55.100 --> 09:02.680
Generally speaking, what we did after the war, after The Space Merchants and we began writing novels more often than short stories.

09:03.540 --> 09:09.800
Cyril would come out to my house in Red Bank, New Jersey, where we kept the room for him with his own typewriter

09:09.800 --> 09:19.120
and we'd sit around and talk for a while and discuss general areas we were interested in writing about, maybe some characters.

09:20.200 --> 09:24.960
And then we'd flip a coin and the loser would go up to the third floor and write the first four pages.

09:25.440 --> 09:30.280
And he'd come down and say, you're on, the other person would go up and write the next four pages.

09:30.400 --> 09:36.200
And if you do that about 25 or 30 times, you have the rough draft of a complete novel.

09:37.040 --> 09:43.040
Everything got radically rewritten after that because the rough draft was pretty rough but structurally it was all there.

09:45.120 --> 09:50.280
Going back to The Space Merchants, there's one question I can never avoid asking an author.

09:50.440 --> 09:53.380
I'm sure you get these all the time and not sure how you respond to them.

09:53.520 --> 09:58.920
But regarding the ending of the novel, did you intend for that to be optimistic?

09:59.080 --> 10:03.220
They were going to get a new start on Venus, maybe perhaps construct a better society.

10:03.220 --> 10:06.060
Was that the intention there or did you leave it ambiguous?

10:06.480 --> 10:11.920
I left it ambiguous partly because I wasn't feeling very positive at the time.

10:12.060 --> 10:19.980
The novel was written in 1952 in their abouts, which was a pretty grimy period in the history of this country.

10:20.300 --> 10:29.900
It was the McCarthy years and the Cold War years and things did not look too, they didn't look even as good as they do now as a matter of fact.

10:29.900 --> 10:35.200
So I wasn't feeling optimistic. I didn't mean to foreclose the possibility of a happy ending.

10:35.800 --> 10:46.780
Actually the novel had two endings. There was a different ending in the magazine here, more upbeat but less organically related to the rest of the novel.

10:47.000 --> 10:49.160
It was put in at the insistence of the magazine editor.

10:51.280 --> 10:55.560
Many readers of course have noticed a very strong social element in your work.

10:55.560 --> 10:59.660
You have much to say about United States society and culture and so forth.

11:00.520 --> 11:02.720
And I believe you've even been involved in politics.

11:03.080 --> 11:14.840
Have you seen yourself in the role of a preacher or a moralist with warnings and science fiction as sort of a pulpit maybe or a soapbox sort of a thing to satirize with?

11:14.840 --> 11:24.060
Oh sure, I think that every writer who really has any interest in what he's doing feels that he has something to say.

11:24.380 --> 11:32.680
There's a remark, I don't remember the source of it, that the proper title of every book is really how to be more like me.

11:33.540 --> 11:41.020
And I think that's how I think that writers are preachers and educators and polemicists and propagandists.

11:41.740 --> 11:47.040
It isn't always political and it isn't always overt but if it isn't there the novel doesn't say anything.

11:47.660 --> 11:54.440
My own interests have been fairly heavily social and political most of my life.

11:54.580 --> 11:58.560
I was active as you mentioned in a lot of political things at one time or another.

11:59.360 --> 12:09.340
I even wrote a book called Practical Politics which is sort of a how to do it manual of how to make the political apparatus work for whatever causes interest in it.

12:09.340 --> 12:15.700
But I do not go out of my way to preach.

12:16.940 --> 12:26.360
It just, I guess, colors everything I say because a lot of myself and as of every other writer I know goes into what I'm writing.

12:27.920 --> 12:33.540
Do you think that science fiction has peculiar qualifications to act as a vehicle for social comment?

12:33.540 --> 12:41.040
I think science fiction has special qualifications to act as a vehicle for discussing anything that affects the human being.

12:41.400 --> 12:44.660
It's a way of looking at the human race from outside objectively.

12:45.200 --> 12:55.020
It's a way of, it's a sort of game playing mechanism for seeing what would happen to human beings under conditions that haven't occurred yet but are very possible.

12:55.740 --> 13:05.700
And I think that that's probably one of the strongest factors accounting for the continual growth in interest in science fiction that seems to have been going on as long as I've been alive.

13:07.440 --> 13:19.380
Okay, in some of your recent works say, Jim and Man Plus, you describe some bad political systems I think where there's a lot of deception, selfish motives, war.

13:19.600 --> 13:22.200
I think even in Jim that was annihilation of the earth.

13:23.780 --> 13:28.440
Does that concentration on the bad aspects of society come from your view of the world?

13:29.620 --> 13:43.620
No, I'm really Pollyanna. I'm a great optimist about the world. I think that we're in for some terrible times and I don't think that most of us will enjoy much of what happens in the next few years.

13:43.620 --> 13:49.620
But I think in the long run the human race will straighten itself out and learn to be able to live better with each other.

13:50.820 --> 13:58.200
But as far as writing, you know, of those concerns, it's not too interesting to write about a utopian.

13:58.660 --> 14:06.400
I mean, what are you going to say about a bunch of people who walk around in togas and eat whole wheat bread, never have any bad thoughts.

14:07.200 --> 14:18.640
It's much more interesting to paint the disasters that may occur as they sort of, I think it's Kingsley Amos who calls that kind of science fiction cautionary literature.

14:19.520 --> 14:23.700
It's not saying what will happen, it's just warning what might happen if we don't watch out.

14:25.140 --> 14:29.320
Okay, I'd like to ask the same question about Jim that I did about space merchants.

14:30.060 --> 14:37.140
The ending of it. I took it as hopefully the part human, part alien society which you envision at the end of the book.

14:37.920 --> 14:40.400
I took that as hopeful. Would I be misreading it?

14:40.880 --> 14:50.560
No, I think that it's hopeful. I think that what I was trying to say in Jim was perhaps a little more over preaching than I usually intend.

14:51.260 --> 14:55.080
And I'm not sure that it came across the way I intended it to.

14:55.680 --> 14:58.480
But the subtitle of Jim is The Making of a Utopia.

14:59.100 --> 15:03.920
And what I was trying to say in the novel is that you can't really plan a utopia.

15:04.040 --> 15:09.920
You cannot construct a society that will make everybody happy and productive and glad to be alive.

15:10.920 --> 15:20.140
Because the happiness, satisfaction, productivity are not a state, they're a process.

15:21.220 --> 15:31.960
And no rigid system can survive giving people maximum opportunities to realize their potential without being flexible and changeable.

15:33.620 --> 15:40.340
Okay, and then in Man Plus, what fascinated me about that book was your examination, the way you did it.

15:40.440 --> 15:41.820
You examined machine intelligence.

15:43.300 --> 15:52.140
Do you think that's going to be possible? The computers that you envision there are linking up and working to survive and sort of taking off?

15:52.140 --> 15:54.000
I think it's an undecided question.

15:54.940 --> 16:08.860
I'm not sure which, it's 50-50 chance in my opinion whether machine intelligence can ever develop the sort of independent self-defining goals that human beings can't.

16:09.660 --> 16:15.080
But I don't think it's impossible. It's just that machines have not yet got that smart.

16:15.080 --> 16:26.460
What I'm pretty sure of is that machines right now are doing things that 50 years ago one would have described as showing human intelligence.

16:27.440 --> 16:29.700
They solve problems very well.

16:30.260 --> 16:37.540
They even do creative things like composing music in any style you like or writing poetry.

16:38.140 --> 16:45.300
It's true that the music and the poetry aren't very good, but most human-generated music and poetry is not very good either.

16:45.900 --> 16:50.760
And I think that maybe better programs can be written for machines and they can be more creative.

16:51.260 --> 16:57.660
But I think when that happens, people will simply redefine that activity as no longer a symptom of intelligence.

16:59.700 --> 17:07.100
Okay, the cyborg that you mentioned in that book too. Do you think man will be partners with machine in that sort of way too?

17:07.100 --> 17:16.960
First of all, I didn't make up the cyborg. The term and the concept was invented by two care-force or NASA.

17:17.300 --> 17:26.820
I've forgotten which researchers in 1958 are about. And it's been used widely in a lot of places, but I didn't make it up.

17:26.820 --> 17:33.160
I think that we already see cyborgs in the sense that a lot of people have mechanical parts keeping them alive.

17:33.700 --> 17:38.760
Pacemakers and artificial plastic veins and arteries and so on.

17:39.520 --> 17:44.680
Not to mention things like glass eyes and prosthetic limbs and false teeth and so on.

17:45.120 --> 17:53.840
And I think we also see a sort of intellectual symbiosis like the cyborg in the link up between human beings and computers.

17:55.100 --> 17:59.840
Computers do not solve problems, do not make up problems and solve them.

18:00.360 --> 18:06.640
But they make it possible for human beings to do that sort of thing in a fraction of the time it used to take them.

18:06.760 --> 18:10.100
Therefore they make the human beings effectively more intelligent than they were.

18:12.460 --> 18:17.880
Okay, that leads me up to Gateway, which is one of my favorite books.

18:18.620 --> 18:21.840
I think you've also written or said that it's one of your favorite novels.

18:21.840 --> 18:31.080
Yeah, it's the novel that I cared most about. I'm not entirely pleased with anything I've written and I'm very displeased with a lot of what I've written.

18:31.420 --> 18:36.020
But Gateway comes as close to being the way I would like it to be, as any novel I've ever written.

18:36.940 --> 18:40.720
Now I think I noticed this. I'm sure many readers did too. In fact, you've commented on it.

18:42.120 --> 18:44.840
There's a departure in style, I think, from your other work.

18:46.040 --> 18:51.500
What were the influences that, well, both caused the idea of the book, perhaps, and also the different kind of style you used in it.

18:52.000 --> 19:00.640
Well, one of the big things in Gateway was that I was under no pressure from anyone but myself to do it the way I thought it should be done.

19:01.140 --> 19:11.200
I had my publisher at that time, a principal publisher, a man named Ian Valentine, who offered me a contract with a substantial advance to write a novel

19:11.200 --> 19:16.100
without saying what the novel was going to be and without imposing any deadline on it when I had to deliver it.

19:16.100 --> 19:25.400
So I didn't have to discuss it with an editor ahead of time or write an outline and limit myself to the opportunities I could take.

19:26.060 --> 19:33.560
And I didn't have the pressure of getting it delivered at a specific date to make me rush it through.

19:34.180 --> 19:41.740
And actually, it took me, I think, six years from the time I signed the contract until I delivered it.

19:41.740 --> 19:45.500
And I had been mulling it over for several years before that.

19:45.800 --> 19:49.140
All in all, I think the book was something like ten years in the gestation.

19:50.100 --> 19:59.660
And also, it's not possible for a writer to produce at the same level all the time.

20:00.100 --> 20:02.880
I don't know why. There are times when I write better than others.

20:04.020 --> 20:12.100
I can't relate them to any outside influence or to my resolution to do well or anything like that.

20:12.380 --> 20:15.720
I just know that sometimes it comes out better than other times.

20:15.940 --> 20:18.520
And Gateway, I think, is one of the times that came out very well.

20:20.140 --> 20:22.400
I wish I could say the same of all of my books.

20:24.300 --> 20:29.040
Did you say the New Wave was an influence on the way you wrote that book, the so-called New Wave in science fiction?

20:29.040 --> 20:38.660
The New Wave was an attempt, I guess, fifteen years ago or more of a number of writers to break away from the traditional kinds of science fiction.

20:38.960 --> 20:41.300
In fact, most of them didn't want to call it science fiction anymore.

20:41.600 --> 20:45.140
They wanted to call it speculative fiction or call it nothing at all.

20:45.780 --> 20:51.980
And they were interested primarily in writing about inner space rather than outer space.

20:52.320 --> 20:57.700
And secondarily, a lot of them, things like the drug culture and rock music and so on.

20:57.700 --> 21:05.100
But in the rather bitter internal struggle that went on in science fiction,

21:05.340 --> 21:07.580
a lot of people taking sides one way or the other.

21:08.260 --> 21:09.900
I think everyone was deeply affected.

21:10.540 --> 21:18.020
And the New Wave, if nothing else, taught a bunch of old dinosaurs like Asimov and Heinlein and me

21:18.540 --> 21:21.840
that there were nontraditional ways of constructing a novel.

21:21.840 --> 21:26.120
You see, most of us had grown up when science fiction was in the pulp magazines

21:26.120 --> 21:29.960
and most of it was written according to some variant of a pulp formula.

21:30.600 --> 21:32.220
It turned out that wasn't necessary.

21:32.800 --> 21:36.420
And I think the New Wave is responsible for teaching us that.

21:37.960 --> 21:42.140
When you were writing Gateway, when you conceived of the idea during that gestation period,

21:42.700 --> 21:45.000
did you intend for there to be a sequel to it at that time?

21:45.300 --> 21:50.960
No, I did not intend for there to be a sequel to it until it was published and people began telling me I ought to write a sequel.

21:51.900 --> 21:53.300
That's what I was interested in.

21:53.340 --> 21:57.680
In other words, were these fans, you responded to fan desires in that respect?

21:58.240 --> 22:03.420
Largely to fan desires and also to my publisher who sat on me and insisted.

22:05.280 --> 22:10.140
I wasn't too hard to convince, but I did not have any such plan.

22:10.860 --> 22:17.860
I know that Gateway leaves a lot of questions unanswered and suggests a lot of things that are not made explicit in the novel.

22:18.520 --> 22:25.160
And I did all that on purpose, but not for the sake of preparing a way for a sequel,

22:25.760 --> 22:29.320
but just because I think that's the characteristic of a lot of good science fiction.

22:30.340 --> 22:37.280
When you finish the story, you think of things that let you write your own stories after it.

22:37.620 --> 22:40.040
I mean, that's the sort of thing that Arthur Clarke does very well.

22:40.560 --> 22:42.720
And I think I try to do it whenever I can.

22:42.720 --> 22:48.880
And it just turned out that there was a lot of public pressure to write a sequel.

22:49.620 --> 22:54.200
There's also been public pressure to write another sequel, and I'm just about to sign a contract to do that,

22:54.320 --> 22:57.600
but I swear I had no such intention when I finished Beyond the Blue Event or Rice.

22:58.920 --> 23:00.200
That's what I was going to ask you.

23:01.100 --> 23:04.820
There were still some questions about the Hishi that were open for exploration,

23:04.960 --> 23:06.740
and I wondered if you'd considered another novel about them.

23:06.920 --> 23:09.580
I've considered it, and just a few weeks ago,

23:10.280 --> 23:14.340
I yielded the pressure from my publisher and said I would sign a contract for another book.

23:15.040 --> 23:16.360
I don't plan to go on Beyond that.

23:16.480 --> 23:24.180
I don't want to do Habit Castello Meet the Hishi or Habit and the Hishi go to Hawaii or whatever.

23:25.740 --> 23:29.220
That's going to be the end of it as far as I'm concerned, but I will write one more.

23:29.920 --> 23:31.940
So many authors are doing trilogies these days.

23:32.060 --> 23:34.260
I thought that maybe you'd started out with that idea way back.

23:34.620 --> 23:35.440
No, not me.

23:35.440 --> 23:43.560
A lot of them do, and I kind of present it because I think mostly it's unfair to the reader to give them part of a story.

23:43.820 --> 23:46.020
I don't think that's true about their gateway or Beyond the Blue.

23:46.200 --> 23:48.020
I think they stand up by themselves.

23:50.220 --> 23:54.240
Okay, I'd like to switch for just a few minutes to some questions about your time as an editor.

23:55.420 --> 24:00.520
I think it was during the 60s you served as the editor of Galaxy in some of its satellite publications.

24:01.920 --> 24:08.200
In probably the best science fiction of a decade went through you in that magazine, the best magazine science fiction.

24:08.560 --> 24:13.640
I was interested in how much influence you had on the authors.

24:13.920 --> 24:19.260
You know, your method of encouraging, coaxing, how you worked with them to get the material you did.

24:19.920 --> 24:21.860
What's different with different authors?

24:22.520 --> 24:28.560
The thing that I know best about how to be an editor is that you cannot have a general policy

24:28.560 --> 24:31.540
and apply it to everybody in hope it will work in every case.

24:32.340 --> 24:34.340
Because writers are very diverse human beings.

24:35.360 --> 24:44.320
Some of them respond to long letters of criticism and suggestions and patting on the back or beating over the head.

24:45.120 --> 24:48.900
And some of them do not want any outside influence at all.

24:49.580 --> 24:58.340
One of my favorite writers told me early in our relationship that he was willing to have me buy some stories and reject others.

24:58.660 --> 24:59.640
He didn't want to hear why.

25:00.520 --> 25:05.880
I sent it back, just sent it back and say no and not tell him what I didn't like about it because I upset him.

25:06.560 --> 25:11.400
Other writers wanted to know in great detail not only what I didn't like but what I did like.

25:12.140 --> 25:18.020
And also there are some writers who are very responsive to money and some to whom money means nothing at all.

25:18.220 --> 25:23.440
Not that they are immune to it but they don't want to think in those terms.

25:24.340 --> 25:30.020
And there are some writers who respond to a lot of personal attention and some who really want to be left alone.

25:30.640 --> 25:37.220
And I had to find out something about each writer to find out the best way to deal with them.

25:37.220 --> 25:39.320
I can't say I was always successful either.

25:39.660 --> 25:47.520
There are a number of writers that I think I should have been able to get more good material from and didn't.

25:47.660 --> 25:50.780
And I just missed the combination in those cases.

25:53.120 --> 26:01.140
An editor in that position, the kind of position you had, I would assume that a lot of stories get published because of the editor's help

26:01.140 --> 26:04.600
and whatever kinds of encouragement he gives it would not have been published otherwise.

26:04.600 --> 26:10.580
Quite a few, yeah, especially quite a few stories come to be written because an editor says,

26:11.760 --> 26:16.500
listen you've got a notion here that you are throwing away and you really should expand it.

26:17.100 --> 26:19.280
John Campbell was superb at that sort of thing.

26:19.420 --> 26:27.180
Some of the best stories he published were the result of his telling a writer that he had an idea that he didn't realize he had

26:28.900 --> 26:30.920
and then getting the writer to write it.

26:30.920 --> 26:33.820
And I tried to do that as much as I could too.

26:34.420 --> 26:43.020
But writers do not always know where their ideas come from and do not always know how to deal with outside suggestions.

26:44.040 --> 26:49.800
There's one very good writer who always wanted to comment suggestions.

26:50.780 --> 26:59.600
Who I finally decided I shouldn't ever give any to because the only thing he ever did was not to rewrite a story the way I suggested it,

26:59.600 --> 27:01.460
but to throw it away and write a whole new one.

27:01.680 --> 27:03.660
I was never able to get him to rewrite a line.

27:04.740 --> 27:10.320
As a result there are probably ten or fifteen stories of his that will never be published because he just threw them away.

27:11.640 --> 27:17.000
Hmm. I think IEF was one of the magazines you worked with when you were with Galaxy.

27:17.400 --> 27:18.840
Galaxy and IEF and a couple of others.

27:19.220 --> 27:23.380
Did you get Larry Niven's first story in that IEF magazine?

27:23.380 --> 27:32.400
I published his first story which is a very short one and for which he got a very short paycheck and his next one was a little longer

27:32.400 --> 27:36.000
and he got a little more and the next one was quite a lot longer and he got quite a lot more.

27:36.840 --> 27:44.160
Larry said that if it hadn't been for those three events in that order he could not have gone on being a writer.

27:44.600 --> 27:51.660
So I take some pride in the fact that I was instrumental in making it possible for him to devote his time to writing.

